Classification Models - practical example¶

For the research, we initiated an analysis of traffic collision data to identify factors contributing to the frequency and severity of incidents. The dataset includes a diverse range of variables from over 190,000 records, providing a substantial base for our statistical models. Our primary focus is on the COLLISIONTYPE variable, which categorizes the nature of collisions.

The data will undergo preprocessing to address missing values and convert categorical variables into a machine-readable format. An exploratory data analysis will follow to ascertain the distributions and inter-variable relationships. We will then employ statistical and machine learning algorithms suitable for multi-class classification tasks.

The objective of this study is to develop predictive models that can assist in the formulation of targeted strategies and choose the best based on the performance.

ANOVA¶

To identify the most relevant features for our predictive modeling task, we are conducting statistical tests on our dataset. Our goal is to determine which variables significantly impact the target variable, COLLISIONTYPE. This process involves two key statistical methods: ANOVA for numerical independent variables and the Chi-squared test for categorical variables. By identifying significant variables, we aim to refine our feature selection, ensuring that our model includes variables that are truly influential in predicting collision types.

In [ ]:
from scipy import stats

# ANOVA test for numerical variables
for column in data.columns:
    if data[column].dtype in ['int64', 'float64']:
        groups = data.groupby('COLLISIONTYPE')[column].apply(list)
        F, p = stats.f_oneway(*groups)
        print(f"ANOVA F-value for {column} and target variable: {F}, p-value: {p}")

Chi-squared test¶

For categorical independent variables, we employed the Chi-squared test to assess their association with the target variable COLLISIONTYPE. This test evaluates whether the distribution of occurrences of each category within these variables is independent of the collision types. Variables with high Chi-squared values and low p-values demonstrate a strong association with the target variable.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Loop through each categorical variable
for column in data.columns:
    # Check if the variable is categorical
    if data[column].dtype == 'object':
        # Create a contingency table
        contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data[column], data['COLLISIONTYPE'])

        # Perform the Chi-squared test
        chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

        # Print the results
        print(f"Chi-squared test for {column} and COLLISIONTYPE:")
        print(f"Chi-squared value: {chi2}, p-value: {p}")

        # Optional: Add a condition to print significant results
        if p < 0.05:
            print(f"{column} is significantly associated with COLLISIONTYPE.")
        else:
            print(f"No significant association found between {column} and COLLISIONTYPE.")

The Chi-squared test results show a significant association between most categorical variables and COLLISIONTYPE, except for STATUS. High Chi-squared values and low p-values in variables like LOCATION, JUNCTIONTYPE, SDOT_COLDESC, and others suggest a strong relationship with the collision type. However, caution is needed as these associations do not imply causality, and variables directly related to COLLISIONTYPE (like ST_COLCODE and ST_COLDESC) may produce tautological results. A comprehensive analysis, considering aspects like multicollinearity and overall impact on the model, is essential. These insights will inform which variables to include in the model and which may require further analysis or transformation.

However, it's crucial to assess the balance of our categorical variables. An imbalanced categorical variable, where one or more classes dominate, might not contribute much predictive power and could potentially skew our model's performance. To quantify the balance, we'll calculate an "imbalance index" for each categorical variable. This index is the ratio of the smallest class frequency to the largest class frequency within each variable. Variables with an index close to 1 are balanced, while those closer to 0 are highly imbalanced. We will iterate through all categorical columns, compute their imbalance indices, and decide which variables might need special treatment or exclusion from our model.

In [ ]:
# Identify categorical columns in the DataFrame
categorical_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns

# Initialize a dictionary to store the imbalance index of each variable
imbalance_indices = {}

# Calculate the imbalance index for each categorical variable
for col in categorical_cols:
    # Get the proportion of each class within the column
    value_counts = data[col].value_counts(normalize=True)
    # Find the maximum and minimum proportion
    max_proportion = value_counts.max()
    min_proportion = value_counts.min()
    # Calculate the imbalance index as the ratio of min to max
    imbalance_index = min_proportion / max_proportion
    # Store the index in the dictionary
    imbalance_indices[col] = imbalance_index

# Output the imbalance index for each categorical variable
for col, index in imbalance_indices.items():
    print(f"Imbalance index for {col}: {index:.4f}")

Imputation and encoding¶

To effectively prepare our dataset for the modeling stage, we will proceed to encode all categorical variables using a one-hot encoding scheme, with the exception of numerical and target features. This encoding will convert categorical entries into a series of binary columns, one for each category, which will enable our chosen machine learning algorithms to process the data without the need for inherent numerical value assignments.

nan_dict, empty_col= {}, []

Imputer¶

Missing data can introduce bias and affect the model's performance. For numerical variables, we will apply Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations (MICE), a sophisticated technique that preserves the data structure and inherent relationships. For categorical variables, we will introduce a new 'Missing' category, which avoids the introduction of bias by imputing arbitrary modes or means and acknowledges the absence of data. This preparation ensures that our dataset is comprehensive and robust, enhancing the quality of the insights derived from our model. The MICE method is particularly suitable for large datasets like ours, where the relationships between variables can guide the imputation for a more accurate replacement of missing values.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.experimental import enable_iterative_imputer
from sklearn.impute import IterativeImputer

numerical_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns

# MICE for Numerical Variables
mice_imputer = IterativeImputer()
data[numerical_cols] = mice_imputer.fit_transform(data[numerical_cols])

# 'Missing' Category for Categorical Variables
categorical_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
for col in categorical_cols:
    data[col] = data[col].astype('category')
    data[col] = data[col].cat.add_categories('Missing').fillna('Missing')

sn.heatmap(data.isnull(), cbar=False)

one-hot encoding¶

The next step in our data preprocessing is to transform the categorical variables into a format that can be provided to machine learning algorithms. We will use one-hot encoding, a process that converts categorical variables into a series of binary columns, with each representing a possible category value. This method is chosen because it enables the algorithms to better interpret and utilize the categorical data without assuming ordinal relationships where they might not exist. By maintaining the integrity of the original numerical and time-related columns while encoding the categorical ones, we create a comprehensive dataset ready for advanced analytical modeling

In [ ]:

data_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data_for_encoding, columns=categorical_cols)

# and the original time-related columns.

Before delving into modeling, it's useful to visualize the correlation matrix of the encoded dataset to identify any potential relationships or multicollinearity between features. This heatmap of the correlation matrix provides insights into how each variable may relate to others. From the heatmap, we observe that there are certain blocks of high correlation, which are likely the one-hot encoded variables that represent the same categorical feature. The majority of the matrix shows low correlation between different features, which suggests that our features are mostly independent of each other, a condition that logistic regression models favor.

The diagonal line of perfect correlation represents each variable's relationship with itself. It's also apparent that some variables have a stronger relationship with the 'Encoded_COLLISIONTYPE', which are potential predictors for the outcome variable in the logistic regression model.

Statistical tools¶

Logistic regression¶

As our target data is categorical, we're utilizing logistic regression, which is particularly effective for multi-class classification problems. Our model is set to the 'multinomial' option, making it well-suited for predicting several classes. We've also chosen the 'lbfgs' solver for optimization due to its robustness in handling multi-class cases and set a high number of maximum iterations to ensure adequate convergence (limited 1000 iterations, because of time consumption). Once the model is trained, we'll not only predict the class labels but also compute the probabilities for each class, which can provide more nuanced insights into the model's confidence in its predictions. These probabilities can be especially helpful in decision-making processes where the degree of certainty is crucial.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

The scaled logistic regression model shows an exceptionally high accuracy of approximately 99.86% on the test dataset. This level of performance, while impressive, suggests potential overfitting. It's crucial for us to validate the model further, possibly using cross-validation or a separate validation set, to ensure it generalizes well to new data. We should also review the model's complexity and the features used to avoid data leakage and ensure the model's practical applicability. Testing on an entirely new dataset might provide a more accurate assessment of the model's effectiveness. Our goal is to balance model accuracy with its ability to generalize.

Non-scaled vs scaled model¶

Comparing the results of the first logistic regression model and the model with scaling, we observe significant differences in their performance. The first model achieved an accuracy of around 80.75%, indicating a high but not perfect prediction capability. This model's precision, recall, and F1-scores across various collision types were good, but not optimal, suggesting room for improvement.

On the other hand, the model with scaling demonstrated an almost perfect accuracy of about 99.86%. While this high accuracy initially appears favorable, it raises concerns about overfitting. Such a high level of accuracy is unusual in real-world datasets and suggests that the model might not generalize well to unseen data. This could be a result of the scaling process, which might have amplified certain features' influence, leading to an over-optimized model on the training data.

Cross-validation¶

We can retest model, using cross-validation. For implementing cross-validation on the logistic regression model, we use Scikit-learn's cross_val_score function. This will provide a more robust evaluation by splitting the dataset into multiple folds and assessing the model on each fold. Next code will perform 5-fold cross-validation on our dataset, increased number of iterations (2000) and return the accuracy for each fold. This process is very time demanding - to solve this, we will use only sample of the data (up to 2015).

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Forming sample for the validation
time_split_year = 2015

X_sample = X[X['Year'] <= time_split_year]
y_sample = y_encoded[X['Year'] <= time_split_year]

# Create a logistic regression model with a higher number of iterations
model = LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial', solver='lbfgs', max_iter=2000)

# Perform cross-validation
scores = cross_val_score(model, X_sample, y_sample, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)

# Output the results of cross-validation
print("Cross-Validation Accuracy Scores:", scores)
print("Mean CV Accuracy:", scores.mean())

Cross-Validation Accuracy Scores: [0.92829774 0.91953487 0.92319995 0.91177157 0.91433712]
Mean CV Accuracy: 0.9194282477593043

After performing cross-validation on the logistic regression model, focusing on the data up to the year 2015, we observed the following:

  • The cross-validation process was carried out with multi_class='multinomial' and max_iter=2000 settings on the logistic regression model.

  • The accuracy scores across the 5 folds were consistently high, showcasing the model's stable performance. The scores were as follows: [0.92829774, 0.91953487, 0.92319995, 0.91177157, 0.91433712].

  • The mean cross-validation accuracy was approximately 91.94%, indicating that the model has a strong predictive ability on the data sampled for validation.

Hyperparameter tuning¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

# Hyperparameter values to test
C_values = [0.1, 1, 10]

# iterations
for C_val in C_values:
    print(f"Testing model with C = {C_val}")
    
    # model training
    model = LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial', solver='lbfgs', C=C_val, max_iter=2000)
    model.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

    # predictions
    y_pred_encoded = model.predict(X_test)
    y_pred = label_encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred_encoded)
    y_test = label_encoder.inverse_transform(y_test_encoded)

    # model evaluation
    print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
    print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    print("\n")

Predictive Tools¶

Support Vector Machine (SVM)¶

We are now shifting our focus to the SVM model. SVM is renowned for its robustness and effectiveness, especially in high-dimensional spaces. This model is distinct for its use of a technique known as the kernel trick to transform data and find an optimal boundary between the possible outputs.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

# Initializing the SVC model
svm_model = SVC(kernel='linear')  # we can change the kernel if needed

# Fitting the model to the training data
svm_model.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Predicting on the test set
y_pred_encoded = svm_model.predict(X_test)

y_pred = label_encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred_encoded)

# Evaluating the model
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) Model¶

We now turn our attention to the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) algorithm. KNN is a simple yet powerful machine learning technique that makes predictions based on the proximity of data points in feature space. This model is particularly known for its straightforward logic and ease of interpretation.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

# Initializing the KNN classifier
knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)  # We will start with 5 neighbors

# Fiting the model to the training data
knn.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# predictions on the test set
y_pred_encoded = knn.predict(X_test)

# Decoding the predictions back to original labels for evaluation
y_pred = label_encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred_encoded)

# Evaluating the model
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("First 5 predictions:", y_pred[:5])

In [ ]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

    'metric': ['euclidean', 'manhattan']

knn = KNeighborsClassifier()

# Create GridSearchCV with the KNN model and the extended hyperparameter grid
grid_search = GridSearchCV(knn, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)

# Fit GridSearchCV
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Identify the best hyperparameter values
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_knn = KNeighborsClassifier(**best_params)

# Fit the model with the best hyperparameters

# Predict on the test set

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

Neural Networks¶

For the next phase of the project, we are exploring Neural Networks, which represent a significant leap in complexity and capability from traditional machine learning models. Neural Networks, particularly deep learning models, have gained immense popularity due to their ability to model complex, non-linear relationships in data. For this model we will use Perceptron. A Perceptron is a simple type of Neural Network often used for classification tasks. It's the foundational building block for more complex neural networks.

Scaled model

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import Perceptron
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

# Creating a pipeline with scaler and Perceptron
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('perceptron', Perceptron())
])

# Fitting the pipeline to the training data
pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Making predictions on the test set
y_pred_encoded = pipeline.predict(X_test)

# Extracting the encoded labels for the test set
y_test_numeric = y_test_encoded

# Evaluating the model
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test_numeric, y_pred_encoded))
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test_numeric, y_pred_encoded))

# Decoding the predictions for interpretability
y_pred_inv = label_encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred_encoded)
print("First 5 predictions:", y_pred_inv[:5])

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

# Use the same pipeline with StandardScaler and Perceptron
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('scaler', StandardScaler()),
    ('perceptron', Perceptron())
])

# Number of folds for cross-validation
num_folds = 5

# Perform cross-validation
cv_scores = cross_val_score(pipeline, X_train, y_train_encoded, cv=num_folds, scoring='accuracy')

# Calculate the mean cross-validation score
mean_cv_score = cv_scores.mean()

# Print the cross-validation results
print("Cross-Validation Scores:", cv_scores)
print("Mean Cross-Validation Score:", mean_cv_score)

  • The overall accuracy of the model reached approximately 99.79%, indicating a high level of effectiveness in classification tasks.

  • This marked improvement, particularly in categories that previously showed weaker performance, underscores the impact of feature scaling on the efficiency of neural network models like Perceptrons.

  • However, such high accuracy might also raise questions about potential overfitting, and it's important to validate the model's performance on an independent or more varied dataset to ensure generalizability.

from sklearn.linear_model import Perceptron
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score

# Define the hyperparameter grid
param_grid = {
    'penalty': [None, 'l2', 'l1', 'elasticnet'],
    'alpha': [0.0001, 0.001, 0.01],  # Regularization term
    'max_iter': [1000, 2000, 3000],  # Maximum number of iterations
    'eta0': [1.0, 0.1, 0.01]  # Initial learning rate
}

# Initialize the Perceptron model
perceptron = Perceptron()

# Create GridSearchCV with the Perceptron model and hyperparameter grid
grid_search = GridSearchCV(perceptron, param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)

# Fit GridSearchCV using the training data
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Identify the best hyperparameter values
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
best_perceptron = grid_search.best_estimator_

# Fit the model with the best hyperparameters
best_perceptron.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred = best_perceptron.predict(X_test)

# Decode the predictions back to original labels for evaluation
y_pred_inv = label_encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred)

# Model evaluation
print("Best Hyperparameters:", best_params)
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test_encoded, y_pred))
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test_encoded, y_pred))

Final Conclusion¶

Data Preparation and Exploratory Data Analysis¶

  • We successfully managed the initial phase of handling over 190,000 records of traffic collision data.
  • Our effective management of missing values, encoding of categorical variables, and exploratory data analysis laid a basis for the subsequent modeling.

Model Application and Evaluation¶

  • Logistic Regression: Demonstrated reasonable performance with around 80.75% accuracy. The model showed varying effectiveness across different collision types.
  • Support Vector Machine (SVM): Exhibited exceptional performance with an accuracy of 98.34%. The SVM model, especially with a linear kernel, proved robust across various collision types.
  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN): Initially struggled with an accuracy of about 46.03%, but showed improvement to approximately 74.52% after hyperparameter tuning. The introduction of feature scaling further boosted its performance to around 98.05%.
  • Decision Tree: Achieved an impressive accuracy of about 98.38%. The model was effective in handling the dataset, although there was a potential overfitting concern, which we addressed through cross-validation.
  • Neural Networks (Perceptron): Initially underperformed with an accuracy of 43.8%, but showed a significant improvement to 99.79% after scaling. However, this raised concerns about potential overfitting.

References: Source of the data is https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ravijonnalagadda/capstone-car-accident-serveity/code
